He is more involved in the remaining 3,000 acres of estate, largely given over to wheat, dairy, fruit and vines, but which last year added rapeseed oil to its tally of products destined for Waitrose, the food arm of John Lewis. Lazenby now grows 400 acres of rapeseed, fields of stinging yellow that assault the eye as you drive about this part of Hampshire. Rapeseed has been grown in large quantities in this country only over the past 30 years or so, and was used mainly for biodiesel before it became the source of now-fashionable, health-giving oil.
